explanation:
Why each symbol is needed to check MISRA R: controlling expressions shall not be invariant

- OS_ObjectIdGetById
  - This is the function whose return value is assigned to return_code immediately before the controlling expression. To decide whether the condition (return_code == OS_SUCCESS) can be an invariant you must inspect OS_ObjectIdGetById's implementation (or specification) to see whether it can return varying values at runtime (based on sem_id, mode, token, or errors) or whether it is effectively constant in the build/configuration being analyzed. If OS_ObjectIdGetById always returns the same compile-time constant, the controlling expression would be invariant.

- OS_SUCCESS
  - The controlling expression compares return_code to OS_SUCCESS. You must know whether OS_SUCCESS is a true compile-time constant (macro/enum) and its value; although being a compile-time constant does not by itself make the comparison invariant, knowledge of the constant is required when determining if return_code can ever differ from it (i.e., whether the comparison can evaluate differently at runtime).

- OS_LOCK_MODE_NONE and LOCAL_OBJID_TYPE
  - These parameters are passed into OS_ObjectIdGetById. Their definitions (macros/enums) and semantics may influence internal logic of OS_ObjectIdGetById and therefore whether that function can return different values. If these parameters are constant values that lead OS_ObjectIdGetById to take a constant path, the controlling expression could be invariant.

- osal_id_t and OS_object_token_t
  - The types of sem_id and token are needed to understand whether sem_id (the input) can vary at runtime and whether token can be modified by OS_ObjectIdGetById. If sem_id is a compile-time constant in the calling context or token is not modified, that could affect whether the return from OS_ObjectIdGetById is variable.

- OS_BinSemGive_Impl
  - Although this callee is invoked only inside the guarded branch and does not affect the controlling expression itself, its declaration (or lack of side effects affecting return_code) can confirm that return_code is not changed before the final return except by assignment in the branch. This helps ensure the only relevant assignment for the controlling expression is the prior call to OS_ObjectIdGetById.

Note: The core determination of invariance depends primarily on the implementation/specification of OS_ObjectIdGetById and the runtime variability of sem_id and the mode/type parameters. The other symbols let you assess whether those inputs/parameters are compile-time constants or whether they force OS_ObjectIdGetById to always return the same value.
